<section xml:id="ch5-probability" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

  <title>Chapter 5: Overview of Probability Ideas</title>

  <slide>
    <title>Key Ideas</title>

    <p>
      <term>Probability</term> gives a framework for describing randomness.
    </p>
    <p>
      We will learn about key elements of probability
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Vocabulary: sample space, event, set notation
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Basic properties and rules of probability (union, intersection, complement)
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Conditional probability, sequential events, and independence
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Bayes Theorem: reversing the sequential thinking
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Simple Randomness</title>
    
    <p>
      <term>Probability</term> is the mathematical framework for studying random events.
    </p>
    <p>
      Our <em>intuition</em> begins by thinking about simple random events: counting <em>equally likely</em> possibilities.
      <md>
        \text{Probability of Outcome} = \frac{\text{Number of Ways to Reach Outcome}}{\text{Total Number of Ways for Anything}}
      </md>
      We previously explored this with <term>contingency tables</term>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The following contingency table categorizes taxpayers (in thousands) according to their income level and whether their taxes were audited.
    </p>
    <tabular>
      <row header="yes">
        <cell>Income Level</cell><cell>Audited=Yes</cell><cell>Audited=No</cell><cell>Total</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Under $200,000</cell><cell>839</cell><cell>141,686</cell><cell>142,525</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>$200,000-$1,000,000</cell><cell>72</cell><cell>6,803</cell><cell>6,875</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>More than $1,000,000</cell><cell>23</cell><cell>496</cell><cell>519</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Total</cell><cell>934</cell><cell>148,986</cell><cell>149,919</cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Need to Generalize</title>
    
    <p>
      Not every possibility for every random event of interest is equally likely. We need to create a method to generalize the ideas.
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <term>Sample Space</term>: The set of all possible <term>elementary outcomes</term>, usually <m>S</m> or <m>\Omega</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <term>Event</term>: A <term>subset</term> of the sample space for which we can find probabilities.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <term>Set Notation</term>: When we can <em>list</em> possible outcomes, a set is written with curly braces { } and the outcomes separated by commas. Alternatively, we can state a rule inside the curly braces for what it means to belong.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <term>Probability of Event</term>: For each event, which is a subset <m>A</m>, we will define the probability <m>P(A)</m> as a number from 0 to 1.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      There will be some consistency rules for <m>P(A)</m> that we will discuss later.
    </p>
  </slide>
  <slide>
    <title>Tax Return Example, Revisited</title>
    
        <tabular>
      <row header="yes">
        <cell>Income Level</cell><cell>Audited=Yes</cell><cell>Audited=No</cell><cell>Total</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Under $200,000</cell><cell>839</cell><cell>141,686</cell><cell>142,525</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>$200,000-$1,000,000</cell><cell>72</cell><cell>6,803</cell><cell>6,875</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>More than $1,000,000</cell><cell>23</cell><cell>496</cell><cell>519</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Total</cell><cell>934</cell><cell>148,986</cell><cell>149,919</cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>

    <p>
      Define the sample space, several events of interest, and state the probabilities of those events using <m>P(A)</m>.
    </p>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Probability Rules</title>
    
    <p>
      First, we have basic rules of probability.
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>An event can be empty, <m>A = \emptyset = \{ \}</m>: <m>P(\emptyset) = 0</m></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>An event can be everything, <m>A = S</m>: <m>P(S) = 1</m></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>For every event <m>E</m>: <m>0 \le P(E) \le 1</m></p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
      Second, we need rules for combining events. Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be two events (i.e., subsets).
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The <term>complement</term> of an event <m>A</m>, written <m>A^c</m> or <m>A'</m>, is every outcome that is <em>not in</em> the event. This is the sample space with outcomes in <m>A</m> <em>removed</em>.
          <sidebyside widths="50% 15% 15% 10%">
            <p>
            <md>
              P(A^c) = 1 - P(A)
            </md>
            </p>
            <image source="images/ch-5-event-A.png" width="20%">
              <shortdescription>Venn diagram showing event A as a shaded circle</shortdescription>
            </image>
            <image source="images/ch-5-event-A-complement.png" width="20%">
              <shortdescription>Venn diagram showing the complement of A as everything except the circle A shaded</shortdescription>
            </image>
            <p>
              
            </p>
          </sidebyside>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </slide>
  <slide>
    <title>Union and Intersection</title>
    
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The <term>union</term> of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, written <m>A \cup B</m>, is every outcome that is in <em>at least one of</em> the sets. This is the <em>sum</em> of the outcomes, counting any duplicates only once.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The <term>intersection</term> of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, written <m>A \cap B</m>, is every outcome that is in <em>both of</em> the sets. This is the set of <em>overlapping outcomes</em>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths="25% 25% 25% 25%">
          <image source="images/ch-5-event-A.png" width="20%">
            <shortdescription>Venn diagram showing A as a shaded circle</shortdescription>
          </image>
          <image source="images/ch-5-event-B.png" width="20%">
            <shortdescription>Venn diagram showing B as a shaded circle</shortdescription>
          </image>
          <image source="images/ch-5-event-A-union-B.png" width="20%">
            <shortdescription>Venn diagram showing the union of A and B, shading anything inside A or B</shortdescription>
          </image>
          <image source="images/ch-5-event-A-intersect-B.png" width="20%">
            <shortdescription>Venn diagram showing the intersection of A and B, shading anything both A and B</shortdescription>
          </image>
    </sidebyside>
  </slide>
  <slide>
    <title>Probability of Unions (A or B)</title>
    
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Two events <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are said to be <term>disjoint</term> if <m>A \cap B = \emptyset</m> (empty overlap).
            For any two <em>disjoint</em> sets, we have
            <md>
              P(A \cup B) = P(A) + P(B)
            </md>
            More generally, if the sets are not disjoint, we can't double count outcomes, so
            <md>
              P(A \cup B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A \cap B)
            </md>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Tax Return Example, Revisited for Union</title>
    
        <tabular>
      <row header="yes">
        <cell>Income Level</cell><cell>Audited=Yes</cell><cell>Audited=No</cell><cell>Total</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Under $200,000</cell><cell>839</cell><cell>141,686</cell><cell>142,525</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>$200,000-$1,000,000</cell><cell>72</cell><cell>6,803</cell><cell>6,875</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>More than $1,000,000</cell><cell>23</cell><cell>496</cell><cell>519</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Total</cell><cell>934</cell><cell>148,986</cell><cell>149,919</cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>

    <p>
      Find the probability that:
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
           a tax return reflects an individual in the lowest or the highest bracket. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
           a tax return reflects an individual in the lowest in come bracket or that the individual's return is audited. 
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      Clearly define two events and identify which rule for the probability for unions should be used.
    </p>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Conditional Probability</title>
    
    <p>
      <term>Conditional probability</term> occurs when we are calculating a probability restricted to a <term>given</term> event. We treat that <em>given event</em> as if it were the new sample space and only consider outcomes that would be in that event. This requires using intersection.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be two events. We define the conditional probability of <m>A</m> <em>given</em> <m>B</m> as the probability of outcomes in A when we know we are restricted to B:
      <md>
        P(A | B) = \frac{P(A \cap B)}{P(B)}
      </md>
    </p>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Tax Return Example, Revisited for Conditional Probability</title>
    
        <tabular>
      <row header="yes">
        <cell>Income Level</cell><cell>Audited=Yes</cell><cell>Audited=No</cell><cell>Total</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Under $200,000</cell><cell>839</cell><cell>141,686</cell><cell>142,525</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>$200,000-$1,000,000</cell><cell>72</cell><cell>6,803</cell><cell>6,875</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>More than $1,000,000</cell><cell>23</cell><cell>496</cell><cell>519</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Total</cell><cell>934</cell><cell>148,986</cell><cell>149,919</cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>

    <p>
      Find the conditional probability that:
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
           a tax return is audited given that the tax payer is in the lowest bracket.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
           a tax return is in the lowest bracket given that the tax return is audited.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      Clearly define two events used in the calculation.
    </p>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Probability of Intersection Using Conditional Sequences</title>
    
    <p>
      The definition of conditional probability can be rewritten as a product:
      <md>P(A \cap B) = P(B) \cdot P(A | B)</md>
      We think of this as: To be in <m>A</m> <em>and</em> <m>B</m>, you first must be in <m>B</m> (using regular probability <m>P(B)</m>), and then once you know you are in <m>B</m>, you need to choose an outcome that is in <m>A</m> (using conditional probability <m>P(A | B)</m>).
    </p>
    <p>
      It could have also been defined symmetrically:
      <md>P(A \cap B) = P(A) \cdot P(B | A)</md>
    </p>
  </slide>

<slide>
    <title>Tax Return Example, Sequential Thinking</title>
    
    <sidebyside widths="80% 20%">
      <tabular>
        <row header="yes">
          <cell>Income Level</cell><cell>Audited=Yes</cell><cell>Audited=No</cell><cell>Total</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Under $200,000</cell><cell>839</cell><cell>141,686</cell><cell>142,525</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>$200,000-$1,000,000</cell><cell>72</cell><cell>6,803</cell><cell>6,875</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>More than $1,000,000</cell><cell>23</cell><cell>496</cell><cell>519</cell>
        </row>
